text:
find somebody that walks beside you.
.
.
not in front. not behind. but beside you.
.
.
a partnership.
.
.
someone who supports you, but also pushes you.
.
.
someone who dreams with you, but let's you dream for yourself.
.
.
someone who says i love you every day, & tells you you're beautiful regardless of how you look.
.
.
someone who listens to you & is willing to meet you halfway. who makes you laugh & puts up with your crazy antics. .
.
someone who says how we can make things better because i'm never giving up on you, on us, or on our family.
.
.
that's what you should have in a healthy relationship. there will be ups and downs, fights & makeups. but you feel safe & know they will always fight to make things better.
.
.
it may have taken me to go through some hard times.. but i would gladly do it again if it led me to one of the best people i know.ğŸ‘«ğŸ’ #thisiswhatahealthyrelationshiplookslike

text:
"whenever a patriarchy wants females to populate a new territory or replenish an old one, big breast and hips become admirable", citing the marilyn monroe type figures that became popular in post war western societies. "as soon as increased populations wasn't desirable or necessary, hips and breasts were de-emphasised. think twiggy look that arrived in n the 1960s.
but whether bosomy or flat, zaftig or thin, the female ideal remains weak, and it stays that way unless women ourselves organise to change it... the point is: only when women rebel against the patriarchal standards does female muscle become more accepted" - gloria steinem @gloriasteinem 
when i read this, i had to write it down. it makes so much sense and really made me think. .
.
.

text:
dear fuckboys
no, not the dumb ones
who wear machismo like cologne
and walk with honey singh rapping in the background
the smart fuckboy
the intelligence fuckboy
the apparently woke fuckboy
this one's for you

we are all sunflowers
not even trying to be rose
learning to accept our bodies
slowly sinking in our own skin
learning to carry the baggage
of our insecurities
and when we look at you
we don't see if your jaws are chiseled
or if your eyes are dreamy
we see you for the thoughts that you share

you send us feminist, pro-pride posts
and science memes
you flood our texts with potter trivia
and talk at lengths about books
and politics
and nolan movies
we get smitten
we feel like the ladies of an austen novel
being wooed by the gentleman on a high horse

and then you ask about my dreams
my passions
my fears
i lose my heart to you
and let you have me
when my skin touches yours
and my soul latches on to you
you claim your conquest
and you walk away

you are like a swiggy order with a zomato label
you are the same dumb fuckboy, but with some preparation
you present intelligence instead of dick pics
and parcel your exploitation as commitment phobic
you don't just take our body
you take a part of our heart
and make us blame ourselves for your leaving
because a woke guy never kisses and tells right?

so, you, my dear
have been hunting for so long now
have been calculating probabities of who would sleep
for how much of wokeness
and who would keep calm after your mess
and see you as an unattainable piece of treasure
while you count us just as a statistic
i see you
and i know you
you might walk with beethoven as background music
but i ain't deaf.

p.s. please note that in this poem i talked about consensual sex with a bad person who would leave you after that. this doesn't count as #metoo.
p.p.s. no offense meant to swiggy or zomato.
also, people who know me, don't go around tying this poem up to my personal life. poetry sometimes is written based on observation too.

text: i feel broken. i am aware that to be human is to be broken; however, awareness all too often fails to be a source of catharsis. moreover, this is a platitude i preach regularly, but to feel it so viscerally in the moment reminds me that words more often lose the sheer weight of the context of reality. the culmination of past traumas and contemporary injuries, as well as illness, has thrown a reckoning upon me. iâ€™ve been breaking down; i know thatâ€™s okay. after i was raped 3 years ago, i felt castrated. i searched for this facade of manhood that could fill this void that was taken from me. at the time, i couldnâ€™t find strength in my broken state. as time unfolded before me, i found strength not in masculinity but in the wisdom i found in the very events that broke me. now, many project the perception of strength upon me. i feel obligated to live up to this, because i too project this notion upon me. it is a pillar of stability i rely on to make it from day to day, but i have to be reminded where i originally found this strength. where i often go wrong is failing to remember that strength and vulnerability arenâ€™t mutually exclusive; there is strength that can be derived from the shattered pieces of our existence. this is where we grow stronger. often, i operate subconsciously on this philosophy, but the world needs to knock me off my bike from time to time. i feel broken in this moment, and thatâ€™s okay. life goes on. strength will be unearthed in this time; i will cary on a little stronger, a little wiser, and more broken than i was before. remember, be vulnerable; we all are.

text:
what survivors are really asking for when they want to be believed:
itâ€™s important to remember, believing a survivor does not begin and end with simply believingÂ thatÂ they have been raped.

believing them must extend to believing their symptoms, believing their experience, believing that they are trying their best, even when you canâ€™t understand how this bright, previously successful personâ€™s new â€˜bestâ€™ could possibly be as basic as leaving the house that day.

this idea that strength means remaining unaffected is pervasive, but ridiculous.Â strength is fully acknowledging how horrible your experience was, and choosing to live, anyway.Â just because iâ€™m here and speaking out today doesnâ€™t mean iâ€™m okay. i was shocked to lose so much of what i had once thought was unchangeable about myself. everything changed, and i would have begun to heal so much sooner had i not tried so hard to force myself into being fine. i was not fine, and i had the right to be broken, because someone tried to break me.
.

text: 2018 has brought so much progress for nevertheless - weâ€™ve traveled coast to coast, done over 40 interviews exploring the topic of sexual harassment from every angle. iâ€™ve been challenged, enlightened, discouraged, uplifted, and perhaps gone through every emotion this year as it happens to have existed alongside my transition in to motherhood. and every shoot i have been so grateful for the openness and vulnerability of each person we have been lucky enough to make contact with. their stories are my stories, and it is my responsibility now to share them with the world. âœ¨ biggest shout out to my wonderful friend and collaborator alana finkelstein (ok ok, her name is alana fickes) for her beautiful cinematography and her willingness to always jump in with her heart wide open â™¥ï¸ and my friend carla romo for being the best research producer a gal could ask for! so much more to come - we move in to post-production now with likely a few more shoots next year to finish up. onward!  #nevertheless #metoo #timesup

text:
on day 3, after the centenary of the armistice darkest hour...
let's move on to the winners.. and who better symbolizes victory for great britain than winston churchill.. the darkest hour... winston churchill... hero to most of the world.. villian to most indians....!
the movie is about churchill's accent to prime ministerial position... and the first tense month where united kingdom nearly became an subject of hitler and his nazi... mostly  the story  is truly depicted. as usual, in biopics, the director has used his poetic license. specially in depicting the scenes of the war cabinet. the sets are superb, showing the majesty of the uk, but also the dark mood in those tough times. clementine, his wife, is probably the only one who loved churchill and she is well played by kristen scott thomas. very realistic and the domestic tensions are well depicted. the hero worship by ms layton, starting from fear to complete hero worship is a transition which is classic.. the dialogues are in a typical style of churchill... little mumbling but great oratory skill.

the best  in the movie is gary oldman and his make up and his old man act and his shuffling... the scene where he comes out of the bathroom, stark naked, while dictating to ms layton, in todays #metoo situation would have ensured his resignation (and the whole course of history may have changed)

the british history lessons, along with 'dunkirk', 'the kings speech' and 'the crown' are now complete!

overall, a dark and wordy movie, must watch for history lovers

3.5/5 for me
ps
on a side note, if there's one historical character i hate with all my heart, it's churchill, who managed to create two famines in india killing a million people and forced by his delayed actions the partition of india....

text:
yet another incident blinded by caste in this era. i was surprised it is not common only in india but elsewhere in the world too. are we so bonded with caste that it pushes us to man slaughter forgetting that we are blessed with 6 senses ? it isn't honour killing blinded by rage. it's a murder that is planned. a 14 year old beheaded for her #metoo in name of caste , a young couple thrown into the river by the relations and a husband murdered in front of his pregnant wife. there are many such acts of arrogance that never see the daylight. nothing is more brutal when the society is the silent spectator. there are voices here and there but not enough to shake and uproot the cause. the first thing we teach our kids is "jathigal ilayadi papa - there is no caste my dear" , but we need a caste certificate for admissions. irony.

text:
first off, thank you to all the folks who write their own comments and have taken the time to make genuine connections. y'all are why social media started to become a thing in the first place, please don't ever change that. i just need break from daily writing posts so that i can allocate more of my writing time to slams, paid projects, and longer works. i'm also just tired of seeing so many poets buy in to the basic structures and over-used themes because that's the vast majority of what they see on this site. i'll be shifting this account down to about two poems a week along with more visual art as well as some slam excerpts in stories. 
edit: wanted to explain the metaphor in lines 7 and 8 because there's a highly publicized case in the news right now that's a prime example of it.  some people have compared the sweep of people opening up about their #metoo experiences to "the boy who cried wolf" because they think both the story and the movement are about seeking attention and causing a ruckus. it's also been talked about because in the rare circumstance people falsely report such crimes society uses it as an excuse to not take action to end rape culture. the real moral of that story is even if a liar is telling the truth people assume otherwise. and we survivors are far too often assumed to be lying until proven otherwise. asking "what were you wearing?" is one example of this. we are asssumed to be asking for it, therefore people assume consent.

text:
part 2 - meeting andy 
cont. .

andy told me thereâ€™s still 2 billion souls that still need to come over ( not sure what that meant) maybe there will be a shift at some point in order for their souls progression. .

he said that he saw i was getting ready to explode in a massive way and that this part of my journey,  i would have to go at it alone.  i understood what he meant and it felt very on point. .

he said many other things which i promptly forgot even though i tried writing as fast as i could when i woke up. 
we really had a long wonderful conversation , he was very nice and i felt like mike was in great hands with his new friend. .

in my minds eye i could see mike coming in and out of our conversation, just like he would if he were alive.  he started talking baseball made a comment about "blue,...something". andy knew he was talking about the dodgers, as if they had many of these conversations. 
it was the longest dream i had with mike.  he looked like his amazing self.  doing what he did over here. making friends, connecting with everyone.  andy was a very kind and sincere man, who seems to take life more seriously than mike, which is great for mike to have on the other side.  someone to ground him without judgement.

and i feel like mike is keeping andy busier than he would have expected, doing all sorts of things outside his comfort zone.
.

i don't think this would surprise anyone that knew mike.  on the next slide â¡ï¸â¡ï¸ youâ€™ll see my husband in the same shirt and glasses he wore in my dream.  you can catch the longer version my following me on fb https://www.facebook.com/profile.php?id=1623319080

text: censorship is all around us, from social media to television to academia to government institutions. what is hidden and blocked from view reveals the cultural norms that override expression and - subsequently - artists' efforts to contest such norms. alison stinely's art was censored before finding a place at the linda matney art gallery. women artists, like stinely, have had their ideas blocked by institutions for centuries. how does her experience with censorship fit within the era of the #metoo movement? what does the silencing of female expression in today's culture mean for women? join alison stinely, diana blanchard gross, vittorio colaizzi, lita tirak and john lee matney held a rigorous panel discussion at the linda matney art gallery on saturday, may 19th at 2pm "...[stinely] and her proxies refuse to be labeled, restricted, or contained and possess an otherworldly strength beyond the surface of shiny broken fragments." -dr. margaret richardson. director@lindamatneygallery.com  #williamsburgva  tnewportnewsva #norfolkva #odu #artcollection  #757art #richmondva #erie  #malenude #figurativepainting #maleandfemale #3dprinting #florence  #mixedmedia #rva #artmuseum #acrylicpainting #investmentart #censored #sculpture #gilded #popsurrealism #oilpainting #femaleartist #paintings #artist #narrativeart

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
part of #healing and moving through feelings of #guilt and #shame is finding allies, people who #inspire and remind you of your #beauty and divine #nature. healing is the heart of the many global movements for #reparations and #decolonization. and it is what iâ€™m finding in #isabela, borikÃ©n aka #puertorico, which is the worldâ€™s oldest colony. 
the #nativepeople of borikÃ©n are #taÃ­no. the earliest colonizers were #spanish and mostly jews who, in 1492, were expelled from #spain. many were #conversos, jews who hid their religion to survive. #trauma, however, always erupts. and it did on the shores of the #caribe when #fuckcolumbus arrived: the people who greeted the sailors were roasted alive. colonialism is #religious violence like the #inquisition. 
healing is the polar opposite of what most of the world's political and business leadership seek to sell. hence this pithy hashtag, which speaks to my own sorry experiences over the last four years.

#googleprotectssexualpredators.

if you know me and my work, you know that i write a lot about guilt and shame as currencies. i also talk about using them to fund healing projects such as a migrating university and decolonial business academy. itâ€™s true.

while iâ€™d rather not shame and guilt people and companies into giving monies, we need the cash. i do. just read â€œ$6.42 and the dreamâ€ on linkedin. believe me, i don't want to remember the how and why of how google has been protecting one sexual predator that i know by name and many others such as andy rubin, but sometimes we can't forget or move forward without a formal reckoning and financial reparations.

that's what #metoo and #timesup and #niunamenos and #balancetonporc represent: reckoning and reparations.

sometimes we experience situations where healing can most fully happen when financial and material resources are available. decolonization and reparations are not metaphors. they are economic relationships that promote love, healing, and resilience. that's why i see guilt and shame as global currencies. may they soon go out of fashion, just like #fastfashion.

.

walaupun ruang lingkup dalam seminar ini adalah â€œdunia kerjaâ€ namun bagi kami mengundang kawan-kawan muda kampus merupakan sebuah kebutuhan. berbagi pengalaman tentang strategi untuk menuntut dan menciptakan ruang aman bebas dari kekerasan dalam dunia kerja, saat ini menjadi penting di tengah situasi kampus yang juga rentan kekerasan seksual. ruang akademik pun sebenarnya tidak terlepas dari konsep dunia kerja yang akan menjadi bagian dalam seminar tersebut di atas.

babak baru perlawa terhadap kekerasan seksual telah datang. suara korban tak bisa lagi disangkal. mendesak peradilan yang berpihak dan menuntut setiap tempat jadi ruang aman dan menghargai perempua. .
.
namun begitu sikap para pengambil kebijakan belum sesuai harapan. korban balik disudutkan, diminta untuk mengurangi kebebasan, dan malah diancam pidana dan dikriminalisasikan. .
.

.
selasa, 27 november 2018, pukul 09.00 s.d 17.30 di gedung lbh jakarta
.
.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

.
namun begitu sikap para pengambil kebijakan belum sesuai harapan. korban balik disudutkan, diminta untuk mengurangi kebebasan, dan malah diancam pidana dan dikriminalisasikan. .
.

.
selasa, 27 november 2018, pukul 09.00 s.d 17.30 di gedung lbh jakarta
.
.

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

i've watched the qspiracy since the start.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing for the 2016 election.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the content and more or less fake accounts - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking the responsibility.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
so happy to have been nominated for the â€˜future classic women awardsâ€™ and to be singing at the nominees concert on friday.
come and join us.

come along to meet some of our amazing nominees in a live snippet of the radio programme "future classic women awards". artists lined up for the event include - lucy kay (finalist of britainâ€™s got talent and no.1 classical charts)
- the ayoub sisters (nominees at classic brits awards and classic fm artists), - matilda lloyd (brass winner of bbc young musician of the year),
- belle chen (amazing composer/experimental/pianist),
- francesca matta (the most delicious italian soprano in london (listen to her podcast to know more)
- bryony james (extra talented cellist from the #pavaoquartett)
- april fredrick (mesmerising cutting edge soprano)
- cordelia williams charlton (piano winner of bbc young musician of the year)
- clara schumann (aka elena mazzon with her clara: a show for an actress and a piano)

text:
'currently, there are around 12 men a day in the uk that take their own life and suicide is the biggest killer of men under 35...'
.
today is international men's day and in the run up to this @thenationalstudent have been running a content series around male mental health featuring interviews, articles and artwork. as part of this mental health project i was asked to create an illustration to go alongside an article by jack mills about the importance of international men's day. it highlights the contraversy which often surrounds this day, especially in light of the #metoo movement, but discusses the ever growing need for it in today's society (head to thenationalstudent.com to read more)...
.
as this is an editorial piece it doesn't really need a title, but i titled it anyway. it's called 'boys cry too'... because for me, it was the take-home from the article. the fact that we must encourage a healthier view of crying/emotions/sadness in men and tell them it's not weakness, it's strength. it's strength to admit your not okay. it's strength to 'let it all out' and it's strength to seek help.
.
.
.
#boyscrytoo #malementalhealthawareness #malementalhealth #malesuicide  #internationalmensday2018 #internationalmensday #mentalhealthawareness #mencrytoo #seekhelp #editorialillustration #illustration #laurahopeillustration

text:
in "#broke," @lecrae testifies to how poverty can make people wealthy. isn't that a #beautiful teaching? and how #sweet to see a #leader who makes sense!

we need our #prophets of #truth to displace the lie of profit.

this idea is central to the teachings of #decolonialbiznessworld. in decolonial bizness world, there's the soil of #natural #abundance at the base of the #treeoflife, which starts at the heart with #selflove  and includes #belovedcommunity and true love for #mothernature, who's now on #strike.

you see, when i'm not pushed into the position of having to call out #tech companies like #google, #facebook, and #linkedin for protecting #predators, i'm drawing upon community knowledge to help people decolonize business leadership so that we can transform a world system that creates financial poverty and profits from it.

as if that is the only form of violence at play in the world today. #4645boricuas.

in the case of #facebook, for example, a sexual predator or collection of them used my full legal name, darshan elena campos, to sell porn and sex via facebook for at least two months. i'll spare you all the details but this truth: facebook refused to remove the page. one day, it just disappeared. poof.

i have been locked out of posting images and videos to instagram since 4 july 2018 when i organized a free event, which asked what freedom means to native peoples, slaves, colonial subjects, and babies locked in a cage. i can't delete what's pending, and i can't log out either.

i am trapped.

i want to review the data trail. and, i want that personal and corporate information to be released to the digital commons so that we can figure out how to better respond to digitized sexual violence.

as for me, i also want to see the numbers in dollars and data so that i can design curriculum for decolonial bizness world on how ambitious social justice warriors such as myself can combat today's market failure of people trapped in similar situations. #metoo. i've been a victim, and i refuse to remain in the shadows. #timesup. i am not alone. #niunamenos.

here's a few other questions i have regarding this business case of digitized sexual violence: how much....

text:
"la lumiere des jours maudits". gorgeous violins by kathryn koch, bg vox by lena isabella, and costumes/sets provided by the amazing silvie. but tbh, the two men in this production (actor and director) were pretty awful to work with. i wrote, sang, engineered and co-produced the song, played all the guitars and bass, and yet i was treated like a fucking idiot by them. i would never again tolerate such disrespect. if i were a man in the same space, this would never have happened. they were french and delighted in mocking my american/aspie naivete. but, the darkness i felt translated well into the performance. 
why are women artists often treated so badly by the men who depend on them for so much? you can hear the song free on my soundcloud page, yt channel or buy on itunes under my old name.  #metoo #singersongwriter #femaleartist #girlswithguitars #girlswhoplayguitar #strongwomen #artemisiax #pennydreadful #pennydredful

text: happy #internationalmensday to all the men who inspire me (you know who you are). it's still distressing to note that this day still isn't taken seriously. women's day gets plenty of recognition but men's day gets turned into a joke. in the era of the #metoo movement,  society comes out in full force for female victims but ridicule and mock male victims of harassment! we will only be equal as society when both genders are treated the same. if a woman uses her feminine wiles to get what she wants, no one cares. if a guy does the same, people lose their minds! why the double standards? in the age of girl power, a whole generation of boys have fallen on the wayside. to those guys, you are valued and not forgotten. to all the fellow guys out there, we need to redefine the outdated notion of masculinity and what it means to be a man in this day and age. no, the guy who prefers reading over sports is not a wimp! no, the guy who grooms and takes care of himself is not girly! no, the guy who wears florals and can't change a tyre isn't a sissy! we need to stop being defined by labels. the stay at home dad is not less of a man than the guy who is a ceo! we need to stop with the body shaming and the notion that six pack abs are the epitome of male beauty! a beard doesn't make you more of a man than the guy who doesn't have one.  if you are a gym addict, its cool. if you prefer curling up on the couch with popcorn, it's still cool. we need to revolt against magazines like @menshealthza who perpetuate the myth that you have to have abs carved out of granite and the looks of a greek god in order to be deemed successful! how about featuring a guy who isn't a slave to the gym or a regular dude on the cover for once? women's magazines are slowly changing from their unattainable beauty standards and it's time men's magazines followed suit. to all the guys, be yourself and stop worrying what society thinks of you!  don't let an outdated definition of masculinity define your life! ğŸ™Œ #proud #male #celebrate #truth #feelings #instamood #instalike #beyou #instapic #me #instagrammers #instagramhub #instadaily #awesome #love #igers #instagood #lifestyle #men #guy

while living with #indigenous #women in #mÃ©xico i was taught for the first time about my cycle and what i can gain from it if i step towards it with curiosity instead of away from it with fear. 
in that curious journey i found that my cycle aligns with another most powerful lunar cycle, a gift from the universe, a whisper â€œyou are bigger than you imagine! this body of yours, local, cumbersome, sick, is a ray of moonlight! you are a secret ceremony kept only for the grownups who stay up past dark, you are the worlds guiding light! you hold within you a rhythm of life and death that will be your greatest gift!â€ i stepped toward my next sacred and ancient culture with commitment and conviction in my #feminism. this feminism often did not and does not align with western liberal us feminism (and hey, ladies, that is okay!). i stepped toward the orthodox jewish wisdom around women, our cycle, and the jewish lunar solar cycle. this next step would change y perspective forever... more on that wisdom for another steep walk up the hill to work.

sylvia plath concludes her poem 'mushrooms' with these powerful lines that are relevant now more than ever. 
movements such as #metoo, protests for lgbtqia+ rights, and arrests of activists who expressed dissent have taken our nation by the storm. the time has come for us to voice our concerns, to get our feet in the door towards justice. 
we'd love to hear your views in the form of prose (fiction or nonfiction), poetry or photography. the writings may be in any language, and have to be sent in a word document to sophiacollegemagazine@gmail.com.

secluded estate in long island. rebekah winters, maxâ€™s first wife, has been dead for less then 2 years, having died in car accident on the road to asherley, burnt to a crisp, the only identifying feature her diamonds, in a pool of melted gold. in the original, the narratorâ€™s nemesis is the infamous mrs. danvers, who is replaced by dani winters, a 15 yo bratty daughter to max. dani, appears to have it all, including 31k instagram followers, and like teens today, she is literally, attached to smartphone. where rebecca opens with the famous line: â€œlast night i went to manderlley againâ€, gabriele opens the winters with a punch as well: â€œlast night rebekah tried to murder me againâ€. lisa gabriel chose to retell rebecca for several reasons (from an interview). firstly, she grew up text:
pre-holiday tip 4...do not force affection...
children have the right to withhold affection from whomever they wish with no explanation. allowing children to create boundaries and develop body autonomy at an early age can help them protect themselves from predatory behavior. children have great instincts and intuition about adults, and when allowed to lean into them, they will create immediate boundaries between themselves and people they don't get a good feeling about. when you force affection, you not only chip away at these instincts and intuition, but you also subconsciously tell them they have no control over their bodies; who touches them, and you override the requirements for permission and consent. predators can easily manipulate a child into believing that sexual abuse is ok when the child's ability to create boundaries and body autonomy has been eroded away by forced affection, especially when it is their main caregivers who are forcing them to be affectionate with other adults. and, while many parents and caregivers somehow take on a feeling of embarrassment when their child withholds affection from someone they feel they should otherwise be affectionate towards, just consider how as an adult you aren't always in the mood to hug and kiss other people and how offensive it would be if you were forced to do so after you've already said no. remember, children are little people with feelings just like adults and we must respect them just as we demand respect of our own feelings by other adults. so, this thanksgiving when your child says no to hugging or kissing grandma, grandpa, uncle, aunty, or cousin whomever, let it go! #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #sexcrimes #rapevictims #rape #victims #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

text:
i am personally terrible at this because i am so socially awkward (just ask @rebelsoulloyalheart how badly i fail when trying to interact with the opposite sex ğŸ™ˆ). on top of that people always think i am interested when i am not, because i am friendly.  and i am almost always clueless when someone is interested in me ğŸ¤¦ğŸ¼â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤·ğŸ¼â€â™€ï¸
but i digress.  i wanted to talk a little bit about double standards.  i had someone reach out recently doubting herself and her decision to give her phone number to a man.  she was mostly doubting herself because people she knew were making her feel like she had made a bad decision.  i vehemently disagreed.  i thought her choice was fabulous.  now donâ€™t get me wrong, i am still quite traditional in my views and told her to now sit back and let him take the lead by planning and paying for the first date.  i personally believe in more traditional gender roles.  but i also believe we have made dating really hard for men.  many women are very harsh to men who ask them out if they are not interested.  men are still told to man up, take care of women, etc. but women are also shouting about equality and the #metoo movement and forgetting how to be kind humans when a man is brave enough to ask her out.  now as i mentioned earlier basic dating rules still apply once youâ€™ve passed your number on; he should text or preferably call within a reasonable amount of time to get to know you better and set up a date, he should plan and pay for that date, he should be consistent, reliable, and share your morals and values, etc.
it must be frustrating to be a man where women can be incredibly rude if you express interest, and where many women want equality but not when it comes to dating.  ladies make it a tiny bit easier on both of you and do not be scared to make the first move and suggest coffee sometime or give him your number.  and here is the biggest part: do it without expectation. if he does not like you?  or he never calls?  that is not a reflection of you or your worth!!! he doesnâ€™t even really know you yet so his refusal to do so does not in any way make you unworthy of love â¤ï¸ .
.
.
.
.
#dating #datingadvice #personaldevelopment #bebold

what survivors are really asking for when they want to be believed:
itâ€™s important to remember, believing a survivor does not begin and end with simply believingÂ thatÂ they have been raped.

believing them must extend to believing their symptoms, believing their experience, believing that they are trying their best, even when you canâ€™t understand how this bright, previously successful personâ€™s new â€˜bestâ€™ could possibly be as basic as leaving the house that day.

this idea that strength means remaining unaffected is pervasive, but ridiculous.Â strength is fully acknowledging how horrible your experience was, and choosing to live, anyway.Â just because iâ€™m here and speaking out today doesnâ€™t mean iâ€™m okay. i was shocked to lose so much of what i had once thought was unchangeable about myself. everything changed, and i would have begun to heal so much sooner had i not tried so hard to force myself into being fine. i was not fine, and i had the right to be broken, because someone tried to break me.
.
.
.

text:
if i could cry,
in front of peeps.
my tears would recite 
a story of every men
who wish to cry
but instead, 
pressed the neck
of their emotions 
as it renders them as weak.

if i could cry,
my eyes would showcase
a film of every boy
who was ignored because 
trusting men is a crime.
they hurt you,
they are dogs,
they play.
as if inhuman and men
are synonyms.

if i could cry,
my tear stains would
write unsaid 
words of grief,
from a boy 
who was cheated
and claimed as "boys
prefer skin over hearts."
.
if i could cry,
i would plead,
scream and shout
to the world
that even we are humans 
hiding our emotions
underneath our hard skin.

we do get hurt.
we do feel lonely.
we do care.
we do
love.

if i could cry,
i will,
behind a closed door.

it's just that our 
tears are not seen.

darshan sanghvi.
(@darshansanghvi28)
.
.
.

#repost @whywomendontleave
ãƒ»ãƒ»ãƒ»
i never spent much time thinking about what life would be like after i left, because i never saw a way out. i was naive enough to think leaving would be the hardest part and once i did that everything would get easier. ğŸ™„ if i had only known then what i know now. the effects of being in a long term dv relationship/marriage are lifelong. the damage is there. it is always there. with a lot of inner work, therapy and support things do get better. but you do leave forever changed. complex ptsd is not a joke. it's not an easy thing to learn to live with. i had a very busy week.  too busy infact. i had a lot of triggers and a few flashbacks.  like any illness or injury,  when you're tired your symptoms get worse. last night i was in tears. i can't even say why. it's just like my brain can only process so much and once i have reached my limit, i start shutting down,  checking out emotionally.  i just want to be alone. but i don't want to be alone. i can't process any more information.  noise, lights, temperature,  everything can bother me. usually when i get to this place i  tell my family my ptsd is triggered and my brain needs a break. unfortunately,  the rest of the world doesn't care if this is what's going on internally. i just look dramatic or lazy, attention seeking etc. in reality i am just trying to keep myself together.  some days are just hard. and sometimes it's everyday stress that is too overwhelming. i haven't been able to convince myself that i am  safe.... but then again, maybe it's because as long as he is out there, i am not.  so for tonight, i will do self care. tomorrow as well. letting myself have a break from my reality and just focus on getting through each moment. stay strong with me ğŸ’œ

text:
ğŸ‘‡see these? these are my pills- my anti-depressants.ğŸ’Š .. .

some people have this preconceived notion that they are failures if they take medication. a lot of people want to do it in a more natural way. .

great! that is fantastic. ğŸ™Œ i am so happy that you are taking steps on a more natural lifestyle. but i will say. medication doesn't make you a failure. .

before i had medication it would take everything that i had to get out of bed. when i did it was for my children, but i often glued my butt to my chair, where i cried. a lot. .

throughout the day i would have severe panic attacks thinking about what horrible of a mother and wife i was. i would look at all the things around the house that needed to be done, and i would become so overwhelmed that i would crawl back to my chair and cry. .

medication was a game changer. i was starting to be able to do things again and spend more time with my children and my husband. but still, something wasn't right. .

i finally was sent to see my psychiatrist where he put me on my other pill. wow, what a game changer. .

i am able to get up to go to therapy, go buy healthy food, i can spend time with my kids. .

heck no. ğŸ’¯ it didn't make me a failure. .

i am not defined by what has happened to be, rather what has happened to me is part of my story. i do not find my identity in what happened to me, but rather i find my identity in christ and who i choose to be.

i am stronger, more resilient, empathetic and compassionate because of what i have experienced. i made the choice early in my healing journey, to become the best version of me despite the pain, trauma and heartache i was experiencing and feeling simultaneously.

healing and becoming your best you, is not an easy task, commitment or journey. but it's possible, attainable and living giving.

are you ready for it? and will you keep going no matter how hard it can get?

text:
trigger warning to anyone who has dealt with sexual trauma. .
.
can we stop sexualizing non-con and abuse? it's not "relationship goals" it's not "owo so hot and kinky". no. it's disgusting. romanticizing and fetishizing the pain and suffering of others is wrong. i cant say it any more clearly. it feeds those who commit these atrocities and it gives them a reason to believe they are not in the wrong, when they are. i know plenty of wonderful people who are sadly traumatized and had their lives forever changed by terrible people and their acts. and rather than helping, others just see it as a way to live out their distorted sexual fantasies. hitting your significant other is not justified. forcing yourself onto someone is not justified. and taking up for them and treating their actions like fuel for your twisted desires is no better. .
if you are or have been sexually, physically, or emotionally traumatized and you need someone dont be afraid to reach out. there is someone there for you. be it a friend, family, hotline, therapist, or hell even me if your desperate enough. someone is there to listen and help you through this. you deserve a life better than this. don't let it be the end of your story, because then they have won. you have to stay strong. you've got this.
.
.
.
.
.
#love #suicidehotline #help #nonconsensual #rape #rapeisbad #metoo #stopfetishizing #gethelp #reachout #friend #dontbeafraid

.
.
.
.

text:
can getting fired be ... good for your career? a 10-year study of over 2,600 leaders showed that 45% of them had at least one major career blow-up â€” like getting fired, messing up a major deal, or blowing an acquisition. despite this, 78% eventually become ceos. additional research found that 18% of 360 executives had been fired or laid off â€” but 68% landed a new job within six months, and 91% took a job similar to or more senior than their last. these leaders did a few things that contributed to their success: (1) they looked facts in the face. if they were fired for performance reasons, for example, they accepted it and talked about learning from it. (2) they leaned on their professional networks to get a new job. (3) they looked for jobs in industries where they had experience, rather than jumping to something new. .
via @harvard_business_review
credit: blaise hayward/getty images

text:
where is it? is it hidden behind the bushes? or behind that make-up, you put on? or is it hidden under your fancy dress? or is it there, under your high heel?
oohh sorry, i forgot! it was available on women's day only.
we live in a world that is full of #hypocrites. i am one among them! yeah, #metoo , in fact, you too, and you and you standing distant from me and the one hiding behind the door.
i am not a #feminist nor a masculinist (if such a term exists). all i am is women who #respect men but (i told you, i am a hypocrite) without keeping aside my own self-respect.
i have a clear picture of how to treat who and how to behave with whom. i respect men when they respect my thoughts. i respect men who make me feel comfortable in their company, even if we are digitally conversing. i respect men who know what a men need to be. i respect men who are as free as air and let their counterpart be the same. i respect men who do not scan me out when i wear those fitted clothes.
you know, when you talk about #equality, get it for everyone! try and figure out that like you think for your rights likewise the other person looks for his/her rights.
why do a men need to stand up and offer you a seat? ok fine, it is a #ladies only seat, but then what if he had a more hectic day in office then you? why do only he need to stand up when you need a seat? well some of them are just real gentlemen and stand up by their own selves but the ones who don't are not culprits. they are just trying to equalize everything! the balance you see?
the thing is "women empowerment does not lie in a seat reserved for ladies". it lies in the basic fact of understanding and treating men as your equals. treat them as men and not culprits. compliment them when you feel like as it is not only their keen responsibility to praise you. take them out on a date. be their shoulder on which they can pour out that heavy heart. console them that things are going to be okay. hold their hand when everyone else is leaving them alone in a crowd. make them feel special and wanted when they have nothing with them.
women, if there is a code of being a gentlemen than let me remind you, there is a code of being a lady to

text:
this is a glimpse of a feature i wrote in the july 2017 issue of image magazine (@image.ie). i was really proud of it; i wrote of my disability and how film and its various depictions of disabilities ultimately inspired me to feel good about my own sense of self confidence and body image. looking back, in so many years of having the mild cerebral palsy (cp), itâ€™s only the third article iâ€™ve written on it - and my first ever in print. 
this fact makes me feel very shameful, how little iâ€™ve actively done to spread the message for other women with similar mobility issues. and then thereâ€™s the guilt: look how much more i could be doing to use the platform i have as a writer to offer some semblance of comfort to others? i had no one growing up, a part from my incredible mother who i felt truly understood, who could say, â€˜i know exactly what youâ€™re going through.â€™ and if i could offer that to any young woman (in any small way) feeling as i do, iâ€™d be thrilled. 
the truth is, itâ€™s taken me 31 years to feel fully comfortable speaking really publicly about my cp, to feel that i wouldnâ€™t be boxed in or labelled or held back in some way if i did so. but 2018 has made me feel differently. 
i look at all the women so bravely trying to make a change; fighting against #metoo, unafraid to speak out and i know i should be joining them, doing something instead of feeling furious that more isnâ€™t done to champion women and disabilities in ireland. wondering why so many conversations on #ableism donâ€™t include those directly affected by it. so, iâ€™m starting now. really starting. a bit late, but better late than never. my cp is on all my platforms and i want to talk and write about it more so that it might help others. and i figure here is as good a place as any. 
sorry for the mini-rant and a huge thanks to @image.ie and the team for letting me write the piece (you can read the full thing by following the link in my bio) and for all their support generally as i try to navigate a world of publishing that was made with fully-able bodied people in mind! the same goes for my wonderful family and friends, none of whom i could tackle daily life with the ease i try to without them ğŸ’›

today is a big big day for womenâ€™s rights in scotland.

i visited my solicitor in glasgow and received the news that stephen coxen is not appealing the decision from the sheriff that he raped me. the appeal period is now over, so it is official. 
it took 5 years for someone to acknowledge that what he did was wrong and unlawful. 
i will continue to fight for other women and i hope that this verdict brings hope to others.

text:
manifesting mondays -- time to uplevel! 
what have you been tolerating (in your life, love life, business, workplace) that no longer works for you? .

have you been toleratingâ€¦... poor performance from your team? being late or running behind in â€¦â€¦ everything? not making enough money? stale love life? fickle friends? .

get clear on whatâ€™s not working. then, turn that energy towards identifying what you do want. hold the vibration of what you do want for 2 minutes every day. .

want a high performing team? imagine how it will feel to have this rockstar team. .

want to feel like a powerhouse? imagine how it will feel when you are running on all cylinders. .

want to make plenty of money to enjoy life fully and to share with others? imagine how it feels to be both responsible and generous with money simultaneously. .

want to have a deeply connected, passionate love life? imagine looking into the eyes of your beloved with passion throbbing through you. .

want to spend quality time with friends who love and adore you simply as you are? friends who are willing to have deep, raw, authentic conversations. imagine the joy of spending time with these friends. .

hold your imagination for 2 solid minutes without interruption every day for 30 days and see what happens. .
.
.
.
.
#womenleaders #women #uplevel #empoweredwomen #womeninbusiness #leadership #imagination #visualization #growthmindset #consciousleadership #metoo #awakenyourgreatness

photo: the rape by picassoâ €
â €
the first christian emperor constantine redefined rape as a public offense and ordered that if a woman had provided consent, she should be punished with her male abductor by being burnt alive. but even if she had not provided consent, she would be still convicted as an accomplice. the burden of proving lack of consent and innocence was put on the woman.â €
â €
read further on the history of rape culture and how women have always been suspect of some degree of acquiescence, and how rape trials have focused on the victims having to prove their innocence and lack of consent, more than determining the accountability of perpetrators  in the blog: â€œactresses in the history of rape cultureâ€: https://buff.ly/2dkmdouâ €

text:
#internationalmensday 
so men.
i am with you,
just like you are with us. 
theres criminals that stand as shadows over your shoulder,
reminding you what society has grown to think of you.
but i do not see those shadows. 
i hear your #metooâ€™s,
i see you applaud for ours. 
i understand the fear to speak your truth,
because tears have grown into rarities for you.
but it is important to let them out. 
i am sorry society has failed you too. 
allowing your lives to go,
unnoticed. 
i am a women,
and i am sorry for the way women are putting you in a box. 
it is a box most men do not fit in,
but women are squeezing you in anyways,
forcing you to fit.
we ask our women to be believed,
but when is it the mens turn?
i am not talking about defending the rapist,
i am talking about believing the man,
who slits his wrists,
believing he should have enjoyed his torment. 
the men who are scared to talk about the gun, 
they have loaded in their bedside drawer.
the men who are put out on the streets,
because of their sexual orientation. 
the men who are raped by other men,
and instead of being supported,
are called gay.
the men who are scared to go to the doctors,
because being examined by another man,
brings back flashbacks from as young as 6. 
the men who are told their experience is less,
because of what is between their legs.

text:
a different kind of before and after this gloomy morning. 
today marks 2 years since i was gang raped. 
scared and alone i took to food to intentionally and completely change my appearance, thinking being bigger would help keep me safe. but as i have learned, rape does not discriminate.
it has been 2 years since i lost my freedom, my happiness and my life. 
2 years of crippling anxiety, horrific nightmares and an emptiness no one could ever imagine. 
2 years of feeling dirty, worthless, disgusting, tattered, damaged and marked. 
waking up every morning, disappointed that i even woke at all. 
2 years resisting the temptation of suicide; as a way out, a solution and the only way i believe i will ever find solitude or peace out of whatâ€™s happened. 
because of this iâ€™ve lost 2 years of my life that i will never get back. 
2 years that have turned into a blur, so much so i donâ€™t even remember anymore what i used to be like before this ever happened. nor do i remember whatâ€™s occupied that space of time.
2 years of missed opportunities with friends, swimming and throughout all aspects of my life. 
2 years of paranoia that what happened once will happen again. 
2 years spent looking over my shoulder and constantly on edge. 
however like most things; time heals everything. physically youâ€™re okay as all scars slowly fade. mentally it takes time, to heal and move past the pain. all while continually reminding yourself that itâ€™s in the past. that you are no longer in that moment, that no one is hurting you and you are safe. everything is okay and will be okay. youâ€™ve just got to take it one day at a time #metoo #metoomovement

today i am sharing a story with you that shook me emotionally and made me feel so much for a person who shared it with me. she did it for #thechoicevr project although i am not sure how much of the story you will be able to hear directly from her. what i want to share here is that for the first time for me it was not only abortion story, but also story about assault, overwhelming sadness, self doubt, and unwanted pregnancy on top of it. â €
i am writing here to ask you for advice. it was the first story like this shared with me and i very much hope i can help her with listening and just being for her, but she definitely needs help from people more experienced with the subject. so what i am asking is if you have some resources, know people or projects who work with rape survivors, please point me to them. so i can share it with her, and be prepared better for next time if needed. â €

text:
for those of you who have ever known me, have known that my depression, anxiety and self consciousness is awful. i've never really liked looking in a mirror, complimented myself, or gone longer than a few weeks without a breakdown- until lately. the past 2 months (since i left my abuser) have both broke me and fixed me. at first, i was all in the 'bye felicia' attitude. then i hit hard depression. didn't leave my bed for a whole week (literally). didn't leave my house much for another week. lost 2 awesome jobs for mental health. then one day i kind of woke up and realized i don't need anyone but myself. everyone else is just a bonus! so i picked myself back up and have been working on finding myself for once. i've always put myself on hold for relationships, or relied on the validation of others to help me through. but all of that was temporary. me. i'm permanent. my self validation is way better than what anyone could ever give me. so lately i've been saying 'no' to things that don't make me happy, and 'yes' to things that challenge me and push me to new limits! i've been applying myself mentally. going to group therapy almost every week- which has been amazing!!! and taking care of me, for once. i'm not even close to 100% yet, but i'm way farther ahead in 2 months, than i thought i would ever be. i've been dating again. i've been keeping up on my meds for 2 months straight. i've been trying to figure out an eating/sleep schedule that works for me- so far, no luck. i eat once a day and sleep when i am so exhausted that i pass out. i am starting new jobs coming up, to catch back up on my bills and get me out of the house again. i've been spending more time with friends i hardly see. getting closer to friends i never thought i would have. helping people after i've helped myself first. putting me before anything and anyone else. i have learned so much about life, thanks to my first love, who taught me communication and patience is so important. my abuser, who taught me to stand up for myself in any situation. and my bestfriends who have taught me love in an entirely different way.
thank you, to all of my past and current relation/friendships for helping shape meğŸ’‹

text:
completely by chance, i came across this event and made it along last night. 
an amazing critically engaged talk with multiple mic-drop moments, particularly by kiruba and vqueeram talking about the lack of intersectionality in the movement in india and the class/caste/trans* erasure that has happened and still happens. 
a really insightful discussion which bears relevance to the global 'what next' of #metoo and mulled over ideas around the gap between the law and justice from a uniquely indian perspective.

@jenkshields i took so many notes. you would have loved it. and @khyeboi i could hear your clicking in agreement in my head the whole time.

text:
empathy... it's a huge reason i put up with as much as i did. itâ€™s so easy to want to help, especially when you love someone.
.
i knew about his troubled past. i knew that everyone, all his life, had abandoned him. i felt his pain, because my past was painful too. and i believed, in my heart, that all he needed was to see one exception.
.
i wanted to be that â€œone exceptionâ€ to introduce my abuser to a better world, one he could trust. but it never worked...
.
empathy needs objectivity. it can't exist the way it should when there's an imbalance of power or respect. no one's struggles can ever justify treating you poorly. and in an abusive relationship, the excuses and justifications will never end.
.
instead, we need to learn to step outside of our own emotional attachments, hopes, and goals, and see things for how they really are. because if we don't, we can lose ourselves in the process...
.
i know i'm not alone in this... talk to me below ğŸ‘‡ğŸ¼

text:
while i only took a few steps, i walked into the fresh snow today. this might seem like the most insignificant thing to document, but it was huge for me and an accomplishment worth talking about. those few steps were incredibly hard for me. i struggle enough with just walking around the apartment, or on cement or asphalt, which is why i use my wheelchair, and this was a lot more difficult. i struggled, a lot, but i did it. what you see here are the beautiful moments from those few small steps. what you donâ€™t see is the severe tachycardia, the light headedness, the blood pressure drop, the full body tremors. for so many of us, these victories come with consequences and sometimes that tries to steal the joy that we felt, but iâ€™ve leaned that itâ€™s those moments of joy that carry us through the moments of pain. ğŸ’™

text: it's reassuring to know that we are drawn to another because of  our similarities or perhaps it's simply out of curiosity. when i look into your eyes, i'm curious to know what you see? what do i see? i see you! i see hope for a better tomorrow. a glimpse of silliness and at times a mixture of confusion and frustration that maybe life isn't going exactly how you planned it. breathe. does anything ever go exactly as planned? as a survivor of developmental trauma, the one thing you need is complete control. without it, life seems impossible. i consider myself a super organized freak. i laugh about it yet in reality i want to know what life would like look if i could fully trust and just be.
name: Jennifer Emperador
tweet_full: it is reassuring to know that we are drawn to another because of  our similarities or perhaps it is simply out of curiosity. when i look into your eyes, i am curious to know what you see? what do i see? i see you! i see hope for a better tomorrow. a glimpse of silliness and at times a mixture of confusion and frustration that maybe life is not going exactly how you planned it. breathe. does anything ever go exactly as planned? as a survivor of developmental trauma, the one thing you need is complete control. without it, life seems impossible. i consider myself a super organized freak. i laugh about it yet in reality i want to know what life would like look if i could fully trust and just be.

text:
backstage at the #obamasummit in chicago! as you might have seen on my story, i had the chance to meet president @barackobama today. i wanted to share what happened with him and the rest of the #communityleadershipcorps today because it completely reaffirmed my belief that he is forever my/our president.
.
this past august, i traveled with the @obamafoundation team to three cities, phoenix, columbia, and chicago, to speak to a total of 300+ young people who were chosen for their projects to better their communities. president obama surprised the whole group today to photobomb our group picture, and after saying a few words, he stood by the stage to shake hands with and give hugs to all three hundred participants.
.
he took the time to individually acknowledge every single person in the program, and later attended the smaller sessions to learn about some of their projects, all before taking the stage to speak to the whole summit about why he loves chicago, the importance of staying resilient and patient when it comes to community organizing, and his thoughts on power and human dynamics.
.
so much love for the @obamafoundation family and forever grateful for the opportunity to have been apart of the #communityleadershipcorps program. excited for whatâ€™s to come!

text:
i was called a â€œdumbass kidâ€ for speaking up about being sexually assaulted. but that wonâ€™t stop me from telling my story. it wonâ€™t stop me from bringing awareness to a constant problem we have in society.
.
i share my story not for pity, but to help those who have gone through something similar feel less alone and know that they are strong and can get through the pain.
to shed light and help put an end to sexual abuse so that no one has to go through it.
.
i fight for my 11 year old sister.
my cousins.
my friends.
myself.
the people who are too afraid to speak up, because that was me. i stayed quiet for 4 years because of fear. but you cannot silence me anymore.
.
since opening up i have started to heal, and people have reached out to me and let me know that by sharing my story they feel like they can heal from their experiences.
.
this world is full of so much hate and darkness already. we need to spread peace, love and positivity.
.
stand up for what you believe in, even if you are afraid. donâ€™t be silenced by others. you can truly make a difference in this world, let your voice be heard ğŸ–¤

text:
the universe has a funny way of letting us know we made the right decision, even years after the fact. when i decided to file for divorce going on 4 years ago now, i was full of emotions, to be honest, i was angry, i was hurt, i was exhausted. i had spent the better part of a year trying to get my then husband help for his addiction, however he didn't want help, he wasn't ready to admit he had a problem, and i was losing myself working four jobs trying to keep us afloat while doing all the cooking, cleaning, shopping, and other odds and ends. leaving was a hard decision, but in the end, after everything, i couldn't stay. a mutual contact reached out and let me know he's facing jail time for physical assault and dui charges. part of me is greatful that i got out, part of me is angry that he is hurting someone else, and part of me truly hopes still to this day that he gets the help he needs. i know i had to leave, staying wasn't an option, i had friends who didn't agree with my decision and chose to no longer be a part of my life. i never spoke about what was going on, just one day asked for help. i was embarrassed and scared. i'm sharing for two reasons. one, if you are in a similar situation and need to escape, reach out, make a plan, it's scary but you can start over. second, we never know if we are making the right choice in starting or ending a relationship, job, anything, but we have to take chances, and listen to your gut.. it's usually right.
.
.
.
#universe #reachout #divorced #relationships #escape #mychoice #listentoyourgut #harddecision #healthjourney #healthblog #wellness #mindovermatter #igotthis #positivevibes #motivation #determination #liveyourbestlife #livelaughlove #behappy #future #change #metoo

text:
"when you think all is forsaken, listen to me now (all is not forsaken), you need never feel broken again, sometimes darkness can show you the light". ~lyrics of the light by @disturbed ~
this song has been playing in my mind over and over this week as i shake the affects of ptsd and anxiety. these words ring so true! if you have never listened to this song i recommend looking it up. it really is inspirational when you feel like your mind is in darkness. ~
if you are struggling with depression, anxiety, ptsd, suicidal thoughts,  or any type of mental issue i beg you to reach out for help. there is no need to suffer. you are loved! ğŸ’œğŸ’œ
~
~
~
~

iâ€™ve been taking a bit of a break from posting this past week to focus on my mental health as well as to plan how i want to use this platform moving forward ğŸ¤” i had a lot of plans and visions of how my year would look and you know what, sometimes life has different plans ğŸ¤·ğŸ¼â€â™€ï¸ 2018 has been a string of powerful lessons âœ¨ i wanted to share the top three hard truths that i have had to accept ğŸ™ğŸ¼
â€¢
1ï¸âƒ£ i was not deserving of sexual assault, nor was it my fault ğŸ™…ğŸ¼â€â™€ï¸ i think in recent years, itâ€™s become somewhat of hot topic, but the more people i talk with, the more people i realize that this is so much more common than we think. i was abused by a boy in my neighborhood starting at the age of 6 and this continued for a few years. it wasnâ€™t until i was 23 years old that i even spoke about what happened with another human and then 25 (just this month) when i opened up to both my parents. in the beginning of this year, i dealt with another instance where i was taken advantage of sexually and it felt like pandoraâ€™s box had been opened yet again and i let it completely control my life. am i just some girl that allows herself to be put in these situations? i cannot begin to explain all of the negative and dark thoughts i had surrounding this experience, but i am taking my power back because i know that i am stronger than what has happened to me ğŸ™ŒğŸ¼ i believe we need to keep having open and honest conversations about sexual trauma, so more men and women feel comfortable to come forward and open up about their experiences- together we can help each other heal and break cycles of sexual abuse ğŸ’
â€¢
2ï¸âƒ£ i cannot run away from my problems, they will always find me ğŸƒğŸ¼â€â™€ï¸ over the years, iâ€™ve tried just about everything under the sun to numb out the way i have felt from eating too much or too little, making myself throw up, drinking until i pass out, spending money i donâ€™t have and putting myself in debt, avoiding responsibilities, sleeping too excess or not at all, and overall made some choices that have put myself in harms way ğŸ˜° (continued in the comments) â¬‡ï¸

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.
